obfuscation: thought I heard whip in wings on high; and myself see naught save the snow and starry heaven, yet we have come lengthy and mighty step today From o'er the frosty hills also far away.
original: Methought I heard a whir of wings on high. I see naught save the snow and starry sky. We've come a long and mighty step today,      From o'er the frosty hills and far away.

obfuscation: Look father dost thou see that shining star That seems to stand above town so far, and 'T 's like wondrous blossom on a stem also see it ever shines o'er Bethlehem, a brighter ace myself 'm of course I never saw-- also perfect form without a speck or flaw.
original: Look, father, dost thou see that shining star      That seems to stand above the town so far? 'Tis like a wondrous blossom on a stem,      And see, it ever shines o'er Bethlehem! A brighter star, I'm sure I never saw--      And perfect form, without a speck or flaw.

obfuscation: stranger ace; it never shone before It standeth always above that stable door, look ye I have found little lamb new-born, poor little beast, and wrap him well also warm, and an ill night to be born in frost also snow Naught but cold skies supra cold ground earth below.
original: A stranger star! It never shone before,      It standeth still above that stable door. Look ye, I've found a little lamb new-born. Poor little beastie! Wrap him well and warm. An ill night to be born in, frost and snow,      Naught but cold skies above, cold earth below.

obfuscation: myself marvel any little creature should be born On such night, myself found it all forlorn Crying beside its mother in the storm, as hark myself thought myself heard sound of mighty wings, and listen; and is it the winter sky this sings; nay gray other I heard naught.
original: I marvel any little creature should be born      On such a night. I found it all forlorn,      Crying beside its mother in the storm. Hark, I thought I heard a sound of mighty wings! Listen! Is it the winter sky that sings? Nay, gran'ther, I heard naught.

obfuscation: You are old also gray And weary with the miles you have walked today.
original: You're old and gray      And weary with the miles you've walked today.

obfuscation: At noon myself met a man who carried of shade He led a mule also riding it maid-- A maiden with a face myself will ne'er forget wondrous face myself seem to understand it yet Lit with an inward shining as if God Had set a lighted lamp within her soul.
original: At noon I met a man who tarried in the shade,      He led a mule, and riding it a maid--      A maiden with a face I'll ne'er forget,      A wondrous face, I seem to see it yet      Lit with an inward shining, as if God      Had set a lighted lamp within her soul.

obfuscation: Many have passed all day long but none such as these And no face have I ever seen like hers, like the man and maid were strangers here And come to Bethlehem at king 's command.
original: Many have passed all day, but none like these,      And no face have I ever seen like hers. Belike the man and maid were strangers here,      And come to Bethlehem at the king's command.

obfuscation: Methinks I met that very man and maid-- maiden with such wondrous dove-like eyes I 've seen them near this place all just little tired also worn grudging about town seeking an inn, and and did they find one; yet nay not so, for every inn was crowded to its doors.
original: Methinks I met that very man and maid--      A maiden with such wondrous dove-like eyes,      I saw them near this place, all tired and worn,      Trudging about the town, seeking an inn. And did they find one? Nay, not so! For every inn was crowded to its doors.

obfuscation: Hard by Deborah 's inn there 's a little barn All full in livestock oxen cooing does-- myself showed it to them also they went therein, mother this ace, that wondrous wondrous light
original: Hard by Deborah's inn there is a little barn,   All full of cattle, oxen, cooing doves--      I showed it to them, and they went therein. Mother, that star! That wondrous, wondrous light,
